<paragraph blockId="16.[151,979,725,747]" box="[151,979,725,747]" pageId="16" pageNumber="897">E t y m o l o g y: The specific epithet is an adjective derived from Samothrace.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1058,762,843]" pageId="16" pageNumber="897">
D e s c r i p t i o n: Body length 
<quantity box="[520,603,762,784]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="16" pageNumber="897" unit="mm" value="1.3">1.3 mm</quantity>
; length of forebody 
<quantity box="[822,906,762,784]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="897" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.5 mm</quantity>
. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation box="[151,226,791,813]" captionStart="Figs 9-18" captionStartId="13.[151,191,1459,1481]" captionTargetBox="[156,1042,192,1449]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[152,1045,189,1454]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figs 9-18: Cyrtotyphlus samothracicus (9-14) and Metrotyphlus samothracicus (15-18): (9, 15) habitus; (10, 16) male sternite VIII; (11-14, 17-18) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3738349" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3738349/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="897">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
. Tarsal formula 2, 2, 2 (
<figureCitation box="[474,550,791,813]" captionStart="Figs 19-26" captionStartId="14.[151,191,1459,1481]" captionTargetBox="[159,1035,199,1435]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[152,1037,190,1444]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figs 19-26: Metrotyphlus samothracicus (19), Cephennium samothracicum (20-22), Scydmoraphes samothracicus (23-24), and Apimela procera (25-26): (19) hind leg; (20) habitus; (21-24) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (25) male tergite VIII; (26) male sternite VIII. Scale bars: 20: 0.5 mm; 25-26: 0.2 mm; 19, 21-24: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3738351" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3738351/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="897">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
). Reliably distinguished from other species of the genus only by the male sexual characters.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1059,856,968]" pageId="16" pageNumber="897">
♂: sternites III-VIII with shallow, but extensive median impressions; sternite VIII (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figs 9-18" captionStartId="13.[151,191,1459,1481]" captionTargetBox="[156,1042,192,1449]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[152,1045,189,1454]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figs 9-18: Cyrtotyphlus samothracicus (9-14) and Metrotyphlus samothracicus (15-18): (9, 15) habitus; (10, 16) male sternite VIII; (11-14, 17-18) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3738349" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3738349/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="897">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
) weakly oblong and nearly symmetric, posterior margin with a large median excision; aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[259,371,917,939]" captionStart="Figs 9-18" captionStartId="13.[151,191,1459,1481]" captionTargetBox="[156,1042,192,1449]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[152,1045,189,1454]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figs 9-18: Cyrtotyphlus samothracicus (9-14) and Metrotyphlus samothracicus (15-18): (9, 15) habitus; (10, 16) male sternite VIII; (11-14, 17-18) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3738349" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3738349/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="897">Figs 17-18</figureCitation>
) 
<quantity box="[387,477,916,938]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="16" pageNumber="897" unit="mm" value="0.15">0.15 mm</quantity>
long and, except internal structures, symmetric; internal structures of distinctive shapes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1058,983,1211]" pageId="16" pageNumber="897">
C o m p a r a t i v e n o t e s: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Coiffait" authorityYear="1959" box="[515,650,983,1004]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Metrotyphlus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="897" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[515,650,983,1004]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="897">Metrotyphlus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
COIFFAIT, 1959 previously included twelve species in two subgenera, four in the nominal subgenus and eight in the subgenus 
<taxonomicName box="[151,278,1042,1063]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Metrotyphlus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="897" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Agnotyphlus">
<emphasis box="[151,278,1042,1063]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="897">Agnotyphlus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<bibRefCitation author="COIFFAIT H" box="[297,468,1042,1064]" pageId="16" pageNumber="897" pagination="1 - 651" refId="ref14361" refString="COIFFAIT H. (1972): Coleopteres Staphylinidae de la region palearctique occidentale. I. Generalites, sous-familles: Xantholininae et Leptotyphlinae. - Supplement a la Nouvelle Revue d'Entomologie 2 (2): 1 - 651." type="journal article" year="1972">COIFFAIT, 1972</bibRefCitation>
(SCHÜLKE &amp; SMETANA 2015). Those assigned to 
<taxonomicName box="[151,278,1071,1092]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Metrotyphlus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="897" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Agnotyphlus">
<emphasis box="[151,278,1071,1092]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="897">Agnotyphlus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
had been recorded from the Alpi Apuane and across the southern Alps southeastwards to 
<collectingRegion box="[348,400,1101,1123]" country="Croatia" name="Istarska" pageId="16" pageNumber="897">Istria</collectingRegion>
(
<collectingCountry box="[418,499,1101,1123]" name="Croatia" pageId="16" pageNumber="897">Croatia</collectingCountry>
). Thus, the record of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2019" box="[736,923,1101,1122]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Metrotyphlus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="897" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="samothracicus">
<emphasis box="[736,923,1101,1122]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="897">M. samothracicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
expands the known range of both the genus and the subgenus southeastwards by a distance of more than 
<quantity box="[202,298,1159,1181]" metricMagnitude="6" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="897" unit="km" value="1000.0">1,000 km</quantity>
and suggests that at least 
<taxonomicName box="[566,693,1159,1180]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Metrotyphlus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="897" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Agnotyphlus">
<emphasis box="[566,693,1159,1180]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="897">Agnotyphlus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is far more widespread and diverse than presently known.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1058,1226,1307]" pageId="16" pageNumber="897">
The new species differs from other 
<taxonomicName box="[520,647,1226,1247]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Metrotyphlus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="897" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Agnotyphlus">
<emphasis box="[520,647,1226,1247]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="897">Agnotyphlus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species by the distinctive male primary and secondary sexual characters, particularly the internal structures of the aedeagus. For illustrations of the previously described species see 
<bibRefCitation author="COIFFAIT H" box="[677,844,1285,1307]" pageId="16" pageNumber="897" pagination="1 - 651" refId="ref14361" refString="COIFFAIT H. (1972): Coleopteres Staphylinidae de la region palearctique occidentale. I. Generalites, sous-familles: Xantholininae et Leptotyphlinae. - Supplement a la Nouvelle Revue d'Entomologie 2 (2): 1 - 651." type="journal article" year="1972">COIFFAIT (1972)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="PACE R" box="[893,1025,1285,1307]" pageId="16" pageNumber="897" pagination="1 - 328" refId="ref14571" refString="PACE R. (1997): Coleoptera Staphylinidae Leptotyphlinae. Fauna d'Italia Vol. 34. - Edizioni Calderini, Bologna: i-viii + 1 - 328." type="book chapter" year="1997">PACE (1997)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1058,1322,1432]" pageId="16" pageNumber="897">
D i s t r i b u t i o n a n d n a t u r a l h i s t o r y: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2019" box="[762,1058,1322,1343]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Metrotyphlus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="897" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="samothracicus">
<emphasis box="[762,1058,1322,1343]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="897">Metrotyphlus samothracicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most likely endemic to Samothraki. Despite extensive soil washing in numerous localities, only a single male was found. It was collected in the north of the island in a moist 
<emphasis box="[214,304,1410,1431]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="897">Platanus</emphasis>
forest at an altitude of 
<specimenCount box="[539,610,1410,1432]" pageId="16" pageNumber="897" type="generic">
<quantity box="[539,605,1410,1432]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="16" pageNumber="897" unit="m" value="110.0">110 m</quantity>
.
</specimenCount>
The locality is illustrated in 
<figureCitation box="[900,975,1410,1432]" captionStart="Figs 33-34" captionStartId="17.[151,191,1459,1481]" captionTargetBox="[153,1038,191,1445]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[153,1038,191,1445]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Figs 33-34: Type localities of Metrotyphlus samothracicus (sample number 20) (above) and of Tychobythinus assingi (sample number 14) (below). In the latter locality, Cyrtotyphlus samothracicus was found, too." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3738355" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3738355/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="897">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
